<paragraph id="09C9E9AD398F56C152A998D94E6898CE" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">
Japan, Honshu Island, Shimane Prefecture, Unnan, Oku-Izumo vineyard, 
<geoCoordinate id="A882B9FEB04EDD8B36EAAB105D628A56" degrees="35" direction="north" minutes="17" orientation="latitude" precision="15" seconds="20" value="35.288887">35°17'20&quot;N</geoCoordinate>
, 
<geoCoordinate id="FE25836D8A985234BC3A005A2AAC8E57" degrees="132" direction="east" minutes="55" orientation="longitude" precision="15" seconds="46" value="132.92944">132°55'46&quot;E</geoCoordinate>
, 155 m, leaves of organic Black Olympia table grapes heavily infested with 
<taxonomicName id="B80207D9853F847817B282F259AC4D71" genus="A." lsidName="A. apicalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis id="2DA13D9E34DE3BEF485573D231A5A8EC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">A. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in a covered vineyard collected 4.x.2019, N. Kado, N. Sawamura, T. Adachi-Hagimori, S. V. Triapitsyn, emerged 5.x.2019, S. V. Triapitsyn [1 ♂, UCRC].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FE84848A6DE546AF174C56FBEE90559F" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="1552F635A499266DDE314B8755190CE8" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7F5AF3C00EE7FBBC80BAE3D77A21C380" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Nearctic region: USA (Nebraska); Palaearctic region: Japan (Honshu Island).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9B3640E66841E88508EFB124108B566D" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" type="host">
<paragraph id="40FE8F9E26DBF2C2F752BB7E0A41FC8F" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Host.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8D579D988908883675362037FFFE6301" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">
<taxonomicName id="2A6FE5E0F6298B4A6B30004843CFDEC3" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1825" family="Cicadellidae" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" rank="family">Cicadellidae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName id="11199055274DE157588BA01B2C53DEC4" baseAuthorityName="Nawa" baseAuthorityYear="1913" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Arboridia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Arboridia (Arboridia) apicalis" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis" subGenus="Arboridia">Arboridia (Arboridia) apicalis</taxonomicName>
(Nawa). This tentative host association will need to be confirmed by experimental work using sentinel eggs of this leafhopper.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B42897646BB3162F393D9C85348ED547" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="A8F3B8B0AE175596A1734FC463CB8329" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5791F09CA1D81276DBD8E4AFA270006A" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">
This specimen is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="9838EC16F11693E617AEAD77BBF48487" baseAuthorityName="Blood &amp; Kryger" baseAuthorityYear="1928" class="Insecta" family="Trichogrammatidae" genus="Aphelinoidea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aphelinoidea (Aphelinoidea) waterhousei" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="waterhousei" subGenus="Aphelinoidea">Aphelinoidea (Aphelinoidea) waterhousei</taxonomicName>
(Blood &amp; Kryger) which belongs to the 
<emphasis id="E859C1EA176E17E09A883C24CB572405" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">semifuscipennis</emphasis>
species group of the nominate subgenus of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="80BA4F1EE620F8C33B0FB36A4EDE07E5" authorityName="Girault" authorityYear="1911" class="Insecta" family="Trichogrammatidae" genus="Aphelinoidea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Aphelinoidea" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="2A6B98FD9DED5BD02A42A4582644715E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Aphelinoidea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Girault, formerly placed in the synonymized 
<taxonomicName id="55643E49C34EF2022CA8DAEB7835811C" authority="Aphelinoidea" class="Insecta" family="Trichogrammatidae" genus="Aphelinoidea" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="(Aphelinoidea) subsp. subgenus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" species="waterhousei" subGenus="Aphelinoidea" subSpecies="subgenus">subgenus Aphelinoidea</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="C945ACA5AE441B184CB7B1F046C9CC19" authority="Blood &amp; Kryger, 1928" authorityName="Blood &amp; Kryger" authorityYear="1928" class="Insecta" family="Trichogrammatidae" genus="Diaclava" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Diaclava" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="36D1346DF7667513094B59BA80ABD57C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">Diaclava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Blood &amp; Kryger) (
<bibRefCitation id="0728139D3A336B3C059ECD7EF4D28BED" author="Triapitsyn, SV" journalOrPublisher="Israel Journal of Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" pagination="33 - 81" refId="B34" refString="Triapitsyn, SV, 2018. Review of the Palearctic Aphelinoidea (Hymenoptera: Trichogrammatidae), with focus on the species described by Ś. Nowicki. Israel Journal of Entomology 48 (2): 33 - 81" title="Review of the Palearctic Aphelinoidea (Hymenoptera: Trichogrammatidae), with focus on the species described by Ś. Nowicki." volume="48" year="2018">Triapitsyn 2018</bibRefCitation>
). Like 
<taxonomicName id="8B771D66D97E903A8C80165A51A4611A" genus="A." lsidName="A. waterhousei" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" rank="species" species="waterhousei">
<emphasis id="F9444422231BC6FDB74DE30BF8386C76" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">A. waterhousei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from England, UK, known from the single male specimen, the one from Japan (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="7FFE216C39417EB359F2F382DC739A16" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F6" captionText="Figure 6. Habitus in lateral view a Oligosita sp. female (Taisha, Izumo, Shimane Prefecture, Honshu Island, Japan) b Aphelinoidea (Aphelinoidea) sp. male (Unnan, Shimane Prefecture, Honshu Island, Japan)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.945.51865.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/428258" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">6b</figureCitation>
) has apical segment of the clava contrastingly darker than the light-colored basal segment, and the marginal vein of its fore wing is notably thickened while the stigmal vein is short, inconspicuous. But because the fore wing of the specimen from Japan is notably wider and its marginal setae are relatively shorter (ca. one-third of the greatest fore wing width), it is unlikely to be 
<taxonomicName id="CF1AB1EF26E002EB691D569124D21615" genus="A." lsidName="A. waterhousei" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" rank="species" species="waterhousei">
<emphasis id="DDD70ABF673320E9E1676A4A0FB91650" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="129">A. waterhousei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; rather, it is more similar to the unidentified male specimen from Nebraska, USA which has the same features, as illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation id="0E80CE81710AF63AB9E5DDC8E762D342" author="Triapitsyn, SV" journalOrPublisher="Israel Journal of Entomology" pageId="0" pageNumber="129" pagination="33 - 81" refId="B34" refString="Triapitsyn, SV, 2018. Review of the Palearctic Aphelinoidea (Hymenoptera: Trichogrammatidae), with focus on the species described by Ś. Nowicki. Israel Journal of Entomology 48 (2): 33 - 81" title="Review of the Palearctic Aphelinoidea (Hymenoptera: Trichogrammatidae), with focus on the species described by Ś. Nowicki." volume="48" year="2018">Triapitsyn (2018</bibRefCitation>
: 78, figs 93-97).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
